{"runId":"qwen-qwen3-32b-nitro@2026-05-13T16-18-40-194Z","slug":"naming-things-real-good","locale":"fr","model":"qwen/qwen3-32b:nitro","modelPath":"qwen-qwen3-32b-nitro","createdAt":"2026-05-13T16:18:54.270Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2016-06-01--naming-things-real-good/index.md","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2016-06-01--naming-things-real-good/fr/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/naming-things-real-good/fr/qwen-qwen3-32b-nitro/2026-05-13T16-18-40-194Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"4348eb1f5300a3ebae967b400d51074ed7f1456254aacb9ebb826e7610fa883f","outputHash":"087c8f6d825fce2a48709fa7ee94dd11030066d0286fb98d8fb33ee781d4fbde","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"The article argues that poor naming and schema design in databases—particularly over-specific field names and redundant tables—lead to fragility, duplicated logic, and maintenance challenges. It critiques anti-patterns like `agentEmailPrimary` and fragmented `User`/`Agent` tables, advocating for consolidated schemas with single-word field names (e.g., `email` instead of `agentEmail`). Key principles include eliminating redundant tables, leveraging context from table names, and avoiding \"locked-in\" specificity to improve reusability and durability. The tone is analytical and corrective, targeting developers and database designers, using metaphors like \"shaky Jenga tower\" to frame the risks of poor design. It references normalization debates and emphasizes simplicity over excessive specificity.","totalInputTokens":4006,"totalOutputTokens":4012,"totalCacheReadTokens":512,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":8956,"totalCostUsd":0.0012833599999999999,"pricingSource":"local-openrouter-estimate","telemetry":{"model":"qwen/qwen3-32b:nitro","chunkSize":"6p","totalChunks":4,"totalInputTokens":4006,"totalOutputTokens":4012,"totalCacheReadTokens":512,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":8956,"totalCostUsd":0.0012833599999999999,"p